description: From Middle English waynscot, from Middle Low German wagenschot, assumed to be from wagen (“wagon”) + schot, believed to mean “partition”.

entries.meaning: (architecture) An area of wooden (especially oaken) panelling on the lower part of a room’s walls.

verbs.description: wainscot (third-person singular simple present wainscots, present participle wainscotting, simple past and past participle wainscotted)

entries.meaning: To decorate a wall with a wainscot.
